The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro
 Friday, April 09, 2004 				 A touch of the comic
In todays time and world when the brotherhood of man is at stake, in a world that has long forgotten to laugh at its own follies, it is a welcome relief to watch a play that provides for that much needed comedy which can lighten the mood and brighten life. Shouvaniks production of Washing Machine, written for the stage by Soumitra Basu and directed by Bimal Bandopadhyay, is one such comedy that will provide a long- awaited comic relief to its audience. Washing Machine revolves around the experience of its protagonist, Raja Ray, who finds himself helplessly embroiled in a predicament he is at odds to get out of. Under incessant pressure from his bosses, Raja, who is a salesman, sells a single machine to two clients, a landlord and his tenant. Henceforth events take an unprecedented turn and Raja gets trapped in a complicated situation which finally leads to an amicable end enroute a comic denouement.																								Event: Play in Bengali, Washing Machine, by Shouvanik																								When: Today at 6.30 pm																								Where: Mukta Angan
